  <div slot="quick-answer">
    <p><strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Choose Sonoma when you want more range, better mid-tier value, and wines that often feel fresher and more food-friendly. Choose Napa when you want more concentration, more Cabernet prestige, and a stronger “special bottle” identity.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Sonoma and Napa are close geographically, but they are not interchangeable in style or buying logic. Napa is the more focused prestige machine, especially for Cabernet Sauvignon. Sonoma is broader, less monolithic, and usually stronger once value and variety enter the conversation.</p>

  <h2>Head-To-Head Comparison</h2>
